{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with this child (S5 Surface the ref + source controls on CLI + MCP schemas)]\n\nAudited this child's contribution to the parent's acceptance/success criteria; every absence cross-checked against the WHOLE sibling roster (S1 6d56, S2 70c7, S3 fa49, S4 30b3, S6 1ba5). This child is the client-surface slice (CLI flags + MCP tool-schema args + default wiring + surfacing verified_at_sha). The union of children covers every parent criterion. No uncovered parent criterion. Empty G3 findings list.\n\n4-bucket coverage map (parent AC -> covering child/children; this child's role called out):\n- Parent AC1 (no attested gate reads the working tree; all read a faithful snapshot at the pinned SHA) — FULLY covered by S1 (6d56 materialize core) + S3 (fa49 gate re-rooting). This child contributes the client-facing surface that decouples the verified path from server cwd/branch (its What: \"The MCP server no longer depends on its own cwd/branch for the verified code path; document that REBAR_ROOT only locates the object DB to fetch from\"). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child — it exposes the controls but does not own the re-rooting (its Scope: \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"). Not an absence (S1/S3 cover it).\n- Parent AC2 (signed verdict records verified_at_sha + reproducible over identical content) — FULLY covered by S4 (30b3 record+sign+in-toto) with the immutable-SHA basis from S1. This child is the PRIMARY OWNER of the SURFACING half: its AC2 (every code-reading MCP tool accepts ref+source; attested results surface verified_at_sha) + its AC3 (omitting --ref resolves origin/main->SHA in attested and still signs, pin recorded) make the recorded pin visible to clients. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. the signing itself (S4). Not an absence.\n- Parent AC3 (local mode reads in-place checkout AND cannot produce a signed verdict) — covered by S3 (in-place read) + S4 (signing bar). This child is the PRIMARY OWNER of the SURFACING half: its AC4 (--source=local reachable from BOTH surfaces and reflected as unsigned in the result). Split is clean — S3/S4 enforce behavior, this child surfaces+reflects it; no uncovered half.\n- Parent AC4 (concurrent gates, no git-lock contention / cross-op corruption; atomic population; delete-on-last-close) — FULLY covered by S1 (atomic population) + S2 (single-flight, delete-on-last-close). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child; claims none. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC5 (snapshot cache + janitor reclaim under pressure without disrupting in-flight reads) — FULLY covered by S2. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC6 (private-repo fetch failure surfaces a descriptive, actionable credential error) — FULLY covered by S1 (raises; its AC5) + S6 (documents; its AC2). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC7 (portable: no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback) — FULLY covered by S1 (implementation; its AC4) + S6 (docs; its AC5). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC8 (all six child stories closed; make lint + full test suite green) — STRUCTURAL/meta epic-completion criterion; covered by the existence of all six children (this child is story #5 of 6 in the roster) + each child's own green-bar obligation. Not an absence at this child.\n\nSuccess-criteria narrative (\"every code-reading gate verifies a CLIENT-SPECIFIED, immutable, reproducible snapshot ... never the server's mutable checkout ...; signed verdicts reproducible and bound to verified_at_sha; unsigned local preserves verify-before-push\") decomposes onto AC1-AC3. The \"CLIENT-SPECIFIED\" clause is precisely this child's core deliverable: making ref+source reachable from BOTH the human (CLI) and agent (MCP) surfaces with documented origin/main defaults (its AC1/AC2/AC3) is what lets a distributed team target the exact code version a gate runs against. The \"bound to verified_at_sha\" clause is made client-visible here (surfaced in attested results); the \"unsigned local\" clause is reflected as unsigned in the result here. No uncovered obligation introduced.\n\nNote: this child's \"What\" explicitly delegates underlying behavior to S1-S4 and prose docs to S6 (its Scope: \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4); prose docs (S6)\"). Each delegated obligation is claimed by a named sibling — behavior by S1/S2/S3/S4, ref/source-semantics prose by S6 (its AC3 documents ref/source semantics + origin/main default for CLI and MCP). Covered-by-named-consumer, not absences.\n\nCoverage-pairing note (clean for G3): this child (S5) and S3 (fa49) both list ref+source on the SAME five tool surfaces (review_plan/verify_completion/review_ticket/review_code/scan_spec) — S3 threads the parameters into the gate dispatch, this child exposes them on the CLI/MCP schema with defaults. This is a producer/surface split (parameter threading vs schema exposure), each scoped out of the other (S3 Scope: \"Out: ... CLI/MCP surface schemas (S5)\"; this child Scope: \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"). No double-ownership and no coverage gap — the client-surface obligation is claimed exactly once (here). (Any WHO-threads-it seam concern is a G4 matter, not a G3 union-coverage gap.)\n\nConclusion: this child cleanly covers the client-surface slice (CLI --ref/--source flags, MCP ref/source schema args, origin/main default wiring, surfacing verified_at_sha, reflecting local as unsigned) of the parent criteria — it is the primary owner of the \"client-specified\" clause and the surfacing half of parent AC2/AC3; no parent acceptance/success criterion is left uncovered by the roster. No G3 finding for this pairing."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782520411701755001,"uuid":"070e01b6-7519-4c47-ac92-dfe3b710a508"}